## 3. Component B — Operational Pace Deductions

Pace deductions measure the execution demands the scenario places on the business. All three components are summed, **capped at 25 points**, then multiplied by the Ambition Mass Multiplier.

### Pace Cap — 25 Points Pre-Multiplication

The total Pace deduction is capped at 25 points before the Mass multiplier is applied. This prevents arithmetic compounding from collapsing the score in scenarios where multiple Pace components fire simultaneously. The cap is reached only when multiple components are under serious stress. It does not suppress meaningful signals — it prevents the formula from losing differentiation at the lower bands.

**Maximum post-multiplier Pace contributions:**
- Organic (1.0x): 25 × 1.0 = **25 pts**
- Active Growth (1.5x): 25 × 1.5 = **37.5 pts**
- Aggressive Scaling (2.0x): 25 × 2.0 = **50 pts**

---

### 3.1 Sales Pace

Measures required new client acquisition velocity relative to estimated current baseline pace.

**Calculation:**
```
Churn Replacement/yr = Current Clients × (1 − Retention Rate)
Required Total/yr    = Churn Replacement + (Target Clients − Current Clients) / Years
Ratio                = Required Total / Churn Replacement
```

**Penalty Tiers:**

| Ratio | Deduction | Label |
|---|---|---|
| < 1.5x | 0 pts | Within current capacity |
| 1.5x – 1.99x | 5 pts | Moderate stretch |
| 2.0x – 2.99x | 10 pts | Significant acceleration |
| ≥ 3.0x | 15 pts | Structural transformation required |

---

### 3.2 Hiring Pace

Measures quarterly net new hires as a percentage of current total headcount.

**Calculation:**
```
Net New Per Quarter = (Target FTEs − Current FTEs) / (Years × 4)
Quarterly Rate      = Net New Per Quarter / Current FTEs
```

**Penalty Tiers:**

| Quarterly Rate | Deduction | Label |
|---|---|---|
| ≤ 10% | 0 pts | Manageable growth |
| 11% – 20% | 5 pts | Elevated pace |
| 21% – 30% | 10 pts | Culture strain threshold |
| > 30% | 15 pts | Structural integration risk |

> **Managerial Threshold Penalties — Removed:** The original spec included −10 pt deductions at 8, 15, and 25 FTE milestones. These have been removed. The Hiring Pace graduated tiers already capture speed-of-growth risk. Milestone-based deductions would require organizational structure data not available in the Simulator and would double-count risk already measured by hiring rate.

---

### 3.3 Capacity Utilization

Measures AGI per FTE at the **target state** against efficiency benchmarks.

**Calculation:**
```
Target AGI per FTE = Target AGI / Target FTEs
```

**Penalty Tiers:**

| AGI per FTE (Target State) | Deduction | Label |
|---|---|---|
| ≥ $160,000 | 0 pts | Healthy leverage |
| $140,000 – $159,999 | 8 pts | Efficiency under pressure |
| < $140,000 | 15 pts | Delivery model strain |

---

## 4. Component C — Structural Friction Deductions

Friction deductions represent constraints baked into the current business structure that resist growth regardless of execution pace. Applied **flat** — not multiplied by the Mass Multiplier.

---

### 4.1 Retention Friction

Annual client retention rate and its compounding effect on the acquisition burden the business carries into the growth scenario.

| Retention Rate | Deduction | Label |
|---|---|---|
| ≥ 85% | 0 pts | Healthy retention |
| 75% – 84% | 10 pts | Replacement drag |
| < 75% | 20 pts | Treadmill effect |

> **Why the maximum rises to 20 points:** The original spec set a single −15 pt trigger at below 85%. The revised graduated structure reaches 20 pts at the bottom tier to reflect the non-linear relationship between churn and growth difficulty. Below 75% retention, 25%+ of the client base must be replaced annually just to stay flat — at that rate, a growth scenario is mathematically a different problem, not just a harder version of the same one.

**Replacement burden reference:**

| Retention | Annual Replacement | Net New Needed to Grow 20% |
|---|---|---|
| 90% | 10% of base | 30% of base |
| 85% | 15% of base | 35% of base |
| 80% | 20% of base | 40% of base |
| 75% | 25% of base | 45% of base |
| 70% | 30% of base | 50% of base |

---

### 4.2 Profit Friction

Current gross profit margin as a measure of the capital buffer available to fund execution costs during the growth push.

| Margin | Deduction | Label |
|---|---|---|
| ≥ 25% | 0 pts | Full tank |
| 20% – 24% | 3 pts | Adequate fuel |
| 15% – 19% | 8 pts | Half tank |
| 10% – 14% | 13 pts | Low fuel |
| < 10% | 18 pts | Empty tank |

---

### 4.3 Concentration Friction

Whether the current client portfolio carries meaningful single-client concentration risk.

**Proxy Calculation (front-end derivable, no individual client data needed):**
```
If (1.5 × Average ACV) / Current AGI > 0.15
  → Simplified: If Client Count < 10, flag fires
```

| Condition | Deduction | Label |
|---|---|---|
| Client Count ≥ 10 | 0 pts | Distributed portfolio |
| Client Count < 10 | 10 pts | Concentration risk |

> **Why binary:** Concentration Friction is intentionally kept as a binary signal. The risk it represents — a single client departure as a trajectory event — is largely binary in nature. At fewer than 10 clients, the statistical likelihood that at least one client exceeds 15% of AGI is sufficient to flag without further graduation.

---

### 4.4 Positioning Pressure *(Replaces Channel Friction)*

Measures the degree to which the growth scenario requires targeting a materially different client profile than the business currently serves.

**Calculation:**
```
ACV Delta % = (Target ACV − Current ACV) / Current ACV × 100
```

| ACV Delta | Deduction | Label |
|---|---|---|
| < 25% | 0 pts | Pricing evolution |
| 25% – 49% | 5 pts | Upmarket shift |
| ≥ 50% | 10 pts | Repositioning event |

> **Why Positioning Pressure replaces Channel Friction:** Channel Friction depended on Acquisition Channel Mix from the Snapshot — an input that may not be present during a Simulator session. It also partially duplicated the Sales Pace signal by using required sales velocity as a trigger. Positioning Pressure uses only inputs already in the Simulator form (Current ACV, Target ACV), measures a genuinely distinct structural condition (client profile repositioning risk), and is valid in both MRR and Project physics models without conditional logic.

> **Key distinction from Sales Pace:** Higher target ACV simultaneously *helps* Sales Pace (fewer deals needed) and *may trigger* Positioning Pressure (harder deals to close against a different buyer). Both effects are real and appear independently in the score.

