## 6. Score Composition Layer

The GVI score is a single number. The Score Composition Layer adds a second signal that contextualizes **what drove that number** — whether it reflects execution demands, structural constraints, or both. This does not change the score. It changes how the score is interpreted.

### Friction Share Calculation

```
Friction Share = Friction Total / Total Deductions (post-multiplier)

Where:
  Total Deductions = (Pace Subtotal × Mass Multiplier) + Friction Total
```

### Composition Tiers

| Friction Share | Label | What It Communicates |
|---|---|---|
| 0% – 20% | **Ambition-Driven Pressure** | Score is almost entirely a function of the growth target's demands. Structural foundation is clean. |
| 21% – 50% | **Mixed Pressure** | Score reflects execution demands and structural constraints working against each other simultaneously. |
| 51% – 79% | **Structure-Driven Pressure** | Score is primarily a function of current business constraints, not the ambition of the target. |
| 80%+ | **Structural Constraint** | Score is almost entirely driven by foundational friction. The growth target is secondary to the structural reality. |

### Output Format

```
[Score] — [Band Name] / [Composition Label]

Example: 60 — Active Pressure / Ambition-Driven
Example: 67 — Healthy Velocity / Structure-Driven
Example: 22 — Heavy Friction / Mixed Pressure
```

### Sample Composition Notes by Label

These one-sentence notes are appended to the score output to shift the interpretive frame based on what drove the result.

| Label | Sample Note |
|---|---|
| Ambition-Driven | "The pressure in this scenario is a direct expression of the growth target's demands on a structurally sound business — not a signal of foundational weakness." |
| Mixed Pressure | "This score reflects both structural constraints and execution demands working against each other — addressing either dimension in isolation will produce a limited improvement without progress on the other." |
| Structure-Driven | "The pressure in this scenario is primarily structural — current business constraints are contributing more to this score than the demands of the growth target itself." |
| Structural Constraint | "This score is almost entirely driven by the current state of the business. The growth target is not the primary variable — the foundation is." |

> **Implementation note:** The Score Composition Layer is a front-end calculation derived entirely from values the formula already produces. No new inputs required. Compute Friction Share from Friction Total and post-multiplier Total Deductions, then apply conditional display logic for label and note. No backend changes required.

