## 10. Complete Penalty Weight Rationale Table

| Component | Category | Tier | Deduction | Max | One-Sentence Rationale |
|---|---|---|---|---|---|
| Sales Pace | Pace | 1.5x–1.99x ratio | 5 pts | 5 | Moderate acceleration signals sales function demand beginning to exceed steady-state capacity, but remains solvable through process improvement. |
| Sales Pace | Pace | 2.0x–2.99x ratio | 10 pts | 10 | Doubling required acquisition rate introduces non-linear strain on pipeline, conversion capacity, and sales bandwidth that cannot be absorbed through optimization alone. |
| Sales Pace | Pace | ≥ 3.0x ratio | 15 pts | 15 | Tripling acquisition velocity is a structural transformation requirement — a fundamentally different sales motion, not an incremental lift in existing processes. |
| Hiring Pace | Pace | 11–20%/qtr | 5 pts | 5 | Elevated headcount growth places meaningful demand on onboarding and integration without yet exceeding most agencies' absorption capacity. |
| Hiring Pace | Pace | 21–30%/qtr | 10 pts | 10 | At this rate, management bandwidth and institutional knowledge transfer begin to degrade simultaneously during the growth push. |
| Hiring Pace | Pace | > 30%/qtr | 15 pts | 15 | Growth at this pace effectively rebuilds the team every three quarters — a categorically different risk profile than fast hiring. |
| Capacity Util. | Pace | $140K–$160K/FTE | 8 pts | 8 | AGI/FTE approaching $140K signals that revenue growth is diluting delivery leverage rather than compounding it. |
| Capacity Util. | Pace | < $140K/FTE | 15 pts | 15 | Sub-$140K AGI/FTE represents a delivery model subsidizing its own operation — growth investment must be funded from margin that doesn't reliably exist. |
| **Pace Cap** | — | All tiers | **25 pts max** | 25 | Multi-component pace stress rarely materializes in perfect linear combination — the cap prevents arithmetic compounding from collapsing differentiation at lower bands. |
| Retention | Friction | 75%–84% | 10 pts | 10 | Annual replacement burden meaningfully elevates required acquisition volume above what a standard growth scenario would demand. |
| Retention | Friction | < 75% | 20 pts | 20 | Below 75%, the replacement treadmill is severe enough that a growth scenario is mathematically a different problem — not just a harder version. |
| Profit Margin | Friction | 20%–24% | 3 pts | 3 | Adequate margin leaves limited buffer to absorb the execution variance that growth scenarios reliably produce. |
| Profit Margin | Friction | 15%–19% | 8 pts | 8 | Below 20%, capital available to fund sales capacity and talent at growth velocity is meaningfully constrained. |
| Profit Margin | Friction | 10%–14% | 13 pts | 13 | Low-teen margins eliminate the financial buffer to absorb mid-execution setbacks without creating a liquidity event. |
| Profit Margin | Friction | < 10% | 18 pts | 18 | Below 10%, growth investment must effectively be borrowed against future revenue — there is no fuel reserve for what the scenario requires. |
| Concentration | Friction | < 10 clients | 10 pts | 10 | At fewer than ten clients, a single client departure is a trajectory event during a growth push, not just a revenue event. |
| Positioning | Friction | ACV +25–49% | 5 pts | 5 | A meaningful upmarket shift implies real conversion and retention risk as the business moves between its current and target client profile. |
| Positioning | Friction | ACV ≥ 50% | 10 pts | 10 | A 50%+ ACV increase requires qualitative market repositioning — different buyer, different sales motion, different fulfillment expectations — that runs structurally parallel to execution demands. |

### Maximum Score Impact Summary

```
Maximum Friction (flat, uncapped):
  Retention (20) + Profit (18) + Concentration (10) + Positioning (10) = 58 pts

Maximum Pace × Multiplier:
  Organic (1.0x):           25 × 1.0 = 25 pts
  Active Growth (1.5x):     25 × 1.5 = 37.5 pts
  Aggressive Scaling (2.0x): 25 × 2.0 = 50 pts

Theoretical minimums (pre-clamp):
  Organic + max friction:            100 − 25 − 58 = 17  → Critical Strain ✓
  Active Growth + max friction:      100 − 37.5 − 58 = 4.5 → Critical Strain ✓
  Aggressive Scaling + max friction: 100 − 50 − 58 = −8 → clamped to 0 ✓
```

The clamp fires only in the most extreme configuration possible — maximum Pace at maximum multiplier plus maximum Friction simultaneously. In that scenario, landing at 0 rather than −8 is appropriate. In any scenario short of that maximum configuration, the formula produces a positive score with meaningful differentiation.

